Section.Description: Isotopte Atom Count is the number of isotopes that are not most abundant for the corresponding chemical elements. For example, among three isotopes of carbon (i.e., C-12, C-13, and C-14), the isotope atom count considers the C-13 and C-14 atoms, because C-12 is the most abundant isotope of carbon.
